{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17537791","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17537791"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:20:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:20:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16065"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16065","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16065"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.33,0.06,0.04,0.32,0.26]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8756"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97844"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8756","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8756"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16065"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80394"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"145"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4413"},{"type":"tags","id":"4513"},{"type":"tags","id":"12464"},{"type":"tags","id":"12800"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20930"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33386"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33411"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45304"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45305"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45306"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45307"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97844","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97844"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the antenatal clinic at 36 weeks gestation. This is her first pregnancy and has been uncomplicated. She has no significant medical history and takes only pregnancy vitamins. Her body mass index is 32 kg/m2. Her oral glucose tolerance test at 28 weeks was normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The symphysis-fundal height measures 40 cm. A growth scan reveals an estimated fetal weight of 3870g (\u0026gt;95th centile), with normal amniotic fluid volume and umbilical artery Doppler studies.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Induction of labour at around 39 weeks","Serial growth scans and induction at 41 weeks","Immediate induction of labour","Elective caesarean section at 39 weeks","Expectant management with spontaneous labour"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s fetus shows evidence of a large for gestational age infant with estimated fetal weight \u0026gt;95%. The main concern with a large for gestational age infant is the increased risk of shoulder dystocia during vaginal delivery, which can lead to significant neonatal morbidity and mortality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInduction of labour at around 39 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E is recommended in cases of suspected fetal macrosomia to prevent further fetal growth while still allowing adequate time for fetal lung maturity. This approach has been shown to reduce the risk of shoulder dystocia and caesarean delivery compared to expectant management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExpectant management with spontaneous labour\u003C/strong\u003E would allow further fetal growth, potentially increasing the risk of shoulder dystocia and associated complications. The risks of waiting for spontaneous labour outweigh the benefits in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElective caesarean section at 39 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E would be overly interventional for this case unless this patient prefers the option of a caesarean delivery. While caesarean section may be recommended for estimated fetal weights \u0026gt;4500g in diabetic mothers or \u0026gt;5000g in non-diabetic mothers, this patient\u0027s estimated fetal weight does not meet this threshold.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerial growth scans and induction at 41 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E would allow excessive fetal growth and unnecessarily increase the risk of shoulder dystocia. There is no benefit in delaying delivery once fetal macrosomia is identified at term.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate induction of labour\u003C/strong\u003E at 36 weeks would be inappropriate as the risks of late preterm birth outweigh the benefits of preventing further fetal growth. The optimal timing for delivery in cases of suspected macrosomia is around 39 weeks gestation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of a large for gestational age infant requires careful balance between preventing excessive fetal growth and ensuring adequate fetal maturity. Other risk factors for shoulder dystocia should also be considered, including maternal diabetes, obesity, and previous shoulder dystocia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Suspected fetal macrosomia (estimated fetal weight \u003E4000g) is an indication for offering induction of labour at around 39 weeks gestation.","The risk of shoulder dystocia increases significantly with estimated fetal weights above 4500g.","Maternal diabetes is a significant risk factor for fetal macrosomia and shoulder dystocia."],"references":["Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RANZCOG). Diagnosis and management of suspected fetal macrosomia [Internet]. East Melbourne: RANZCOG; 2021 [cited 2024 Nov 22]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Diagnosis-Management-Suspected-Fetal-Macrosomia.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80394"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16065"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80394","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80394"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-09T18:04:25+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-09T23:20:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8756"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97844"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"145",